Furthermore, to investigate the practical applicability of the developed sensor, it was applied for TOB detection in real samples including river water and honey (
                           Table S3

                        ). The obtained results showed the ability of the developed SPCDs- Fe3+ sensor to detect TOB in both samples with acceptable accuracy and precision indicated by the demonstrated mean % recovery and RSD < 2%.

As compared to previously reported SPCDs (presented in 
                           Table S5
                        ), our SPCDs-based sensor is prepared without any intended energy consumption in relatively short time, with very few treatment steps. No special equipment were required for SPCDs sensor preparation as per other methods such as hydrothermal autoclave [8,10,12] or furnace [37]. Moreover, from economical point of view, the proposed preparation method did not waste any edible part of the plant. Additionally, the QY of the obtained SPCDs was markedly higher than previously reported ones. As a conclusion, this work introduced a new sustainable cost-effective source for sweet potato derived CDs with high production yield. Based on these findings, it is highly recommended to collect these roasting residues so that they can be adapted for routine mass production of CDs for different uses.
